### Here is a brief explanation of the code in the question:

 - `TailCall` is a class that represents a recursive call, so instead of doing a recursive call by pushing a new stackframe, we create an instance of `TailCall` which can be intermediate or terminal subclass depending on whether the recursive call is the last call or there will be a next call embedded in it (in the `TailCall` object) using a Supplier (which achieves lazy evaluation). So at any point in time, we either have 1 **referenced** object representing the whole recursion chain, or at most 2 **referenced** objects representing it (and this latter case happens when we start evaluating the `TailCall`&#39;s next call using `eval` method

